summary:
Extends the mandate of MINURCAT until 31 December 2010;

 Notes the commitment of the Government of Chad to assume full responsibility for security and protection of civilians, including refugees, IDPs, and humanitarian personnel;

Outlines specific tasks for the Government of Chad, including ensuring security and protection of civilians, facilitating humanitarian aid, and ensuring security of MINURCAT staff;

Identifies benchmarks for the Government of Chad, including voluntary return and resettlement of IDPs, demilitarization of refugee and IDP camps, and improvement in the capacity of Chadian authorities;

Establishes a joint Government of Chad/UN high-level Working Group to assess the situation on the ground and progress towards meeting benchmarks;

Requests the Government of Chad to submit a plan to ensure sustainment of the DIS post-MINURCAT;

Reduces the military component of MINURCAT to 2,200 personnel and 25 military liaison officers;

Directs the Secretary-General to implement the withdrawal of exceeding troops by 15 July 2010 and complete withdrawal of all uniformed and civilian MINURCAT components by 31 December 2010;

Defines MINURCAT's mandate in eastern Chad and the north-eastern Central African Republic, including selecting, mentoring, and training DIS elements, providing logistical assistance to UNHCR, and promoting and protecting human rights.
Here is a concise summary of the Security Council document:

The Security Council:

 Authorizes MINURCAT to support efforts to strengthen the capacity of the Government of Chad and civil society through training in international human rights standards (para 8(vi)).

 Authorizes MINURCAT to assist the Government of Chad in promoting the rule of law, including support for an independent judiciary and a strengthened legal system (para 8(vii)).

 Decides that MINURCAT shall be authorized to fulfill specific functions in eastern Chad, including providing security for UN personnel, maintaining situational awareness, and providing medical evacuation support (para 9).

 Authorizes MINURCAT to respond to imminent threats of violence to civilians in its immediate vicinity (para 10).

 Authorizes MINURCAT to fulfill specific functions in the north-eastern Central African Republic, including contributing to a more secure environment and protecting UN personnel (para 11).
